According to the [[Book of Ether]] in the [[Book of Mormon]], '''Akish''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|eɪ|k|ɪ|ʃ}})<ref>[http://www.lds.org/scriptures/bofm/pronunciation?lang=eng LDS.org: "Book of Mormon Pronunciation Guide"] (retrieved 2012-02-25), [[Wikipedia:IPA for English|IPA]]-ified from «ā´kĭsh»</ref> was a prominent figure among the [[Jaredites]]. In the book's narrative, Akish first established [[Secret combination (Latter Day Saints)|secret combinations]], nearly destroying their civilization. He did so when Jared's daughter danced before him, and to marry her, Akish conspired with Jared to dethrone his father, [[Lineage of Ether#Reign of Omer|Omer]], the legitimate king. Later, Akish killed Jared and took the kingdom for himself.<ref>''Equal rites: the Book of Mormon, Masonry, gender, and American culture'', Clyde R Forsberg. New York: Columbia University Press, 2004. {{ISBN|978-0-231-12640-3}}</ref><ref>''An approach to the study of Book of Mormon geography'', by J A Washburn;  Jesse Nile Washburn. Provo, Utah: New era Pub. Co., 1939, {{OCLC|4391986}} p.30-32, p.41-44 [https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=mg9lrUmbtJ4C&oi=fnd&pg=PA7&dq=Akish+Jaredites&ots=3FdO-16xy-&sig=eUPQyeEQQ5RpEFtluJQE0yj5V8w Google Books]</ref>

''Akîsh'' may be a transliteration of אָכִישׁ ([[Achish]] in the [[King James Bible]]). [[David Rohl]] writes that the name may be a shortened form of ''[[Akishimige]]'', a [[Hurrian]] name meaning "the Sun God has given".<ref>David Rohl, ''A Test of Time'' (1995), {{ISBN|0-7126-5913-7}}</ref>

