'''Devachan''' (compound word; Sanskrit 'deva', gods, and the Tibetan word 'chan' Wylie: 'can', possessing, having, subject to) is the "dwelling of the gods" according to the original teachings of [[Theosophy (Blavatskian)|Theosophy]] as formulated by [[H.P. Blavatsky]].
==Theosophy== ''Devachan'' is regarded as the place where most souls go after death where desires are gratified, corresponding to the [[Christian]] belief in Heaven. However, Devachan is a temporary, intermediate state of being before the soul's eventual rebirth into the physical world.<ref>H.P. Blavatsky, ''The Theosophical Glossary''. Theosophical Publishing Society, 1892, page 98</ref> {{quotebox | quote = Through Wisdom and Knowledge, one can reach Nirvana and be free from the cycle of birth and death, and even the "false bliss" of Devachan. | source = H.P. Blavatsky, ''The Secret Doctrine'' <ref>H.P. Blavatsky, ''The Secret Doctrine''. Theosophical Publishing Society, 1888, page 39</ref> | width = 75% | align = center}}
=== According to C.W. Leadbeater=== [[C.W. Leadbeater]] located the "Devachan" on the [[mental plane]] many miles far above the surface of Earth. While those souls at the [[Initiation (Theosophy)|zeroth level of initiation]] (the vast majority of the inhabitants of Earth) go to [[The Summerland#Summerland in Theosophy|Summerland]] (located on the [[astral plane]] only a few miles above the surface of Earth) when they die, those who have reached the [[Initiation (Theosophy)|first, second, or third levels of initiation]] go to Devachan when they die. The final Heaven where souls at the [[Initiation (Theosophy)|fourth level of initiation]] (those souls who have become [[arhats]] and no longer need to reincarnate) is called [[Spiritual Hierarchy#Cosmic beings governing Nirvana|Nirvana]]. When reaching the fourth level of initiation, one can become a [[pratyekabuddha]] and enter Nirvana right away, or become a [[List of Buddhas|buddha]] or [[bodhisattva]] and teach others before entering. One can also choose to become a [[Masters of the Ancient Wisdom|Master]] in the [[Spiritual Hierarchy]] upon reaching the fourth level of initiation—then one's entrance into Nirvana is delayed for millions, billions, or trillions of years until one has completed climbing the [[Initiation (Theosophy)#Levels of initiation beyond the tenth level|ladder of initiation]] by completing one's tasks as a Master in the Spiritual Hierarchy.<ref>Leadbeater, C.W. ''A Textbook of Theosophy'' 1912</ref><ref>Leadbeater, C.W. ''The Masters and the Path'' 1926,</ref><ref>[http://users.ez2.net/nick29/theosophy/lessons06.htm Various Levels of the Afterlife in Theosophy:]</ref>
==Anthroposophy== From the perspective of [[anthroposophy]] [[Rudolf Steiner]] asserts that the Lower Devachan (or the Heavenly World) and Higher Devachan (or the World of Reason) are two "supersensible" realms, above the [[astral realm]], associated with [[emotions]] and [[Volition (psychology)|will impulse]], respectively. In comparison, the mental realm is associated with [[thought]].<ref>{{Cite web |author= [[Rudolf Steiner|Steiner, Rudolf]] |url= http://wn.rsarchive.org/Lectures/JeshuPandira/19111104p02.html |title= Jeshu ben Pandira Who Prepared the Way for an Understanding of the Christ Impulse (part I) |publisher= [[Rudolf Steiner Archive]] }} The first of two lectures delivered at Leipzig on November 4 and 5, 1911. GA# 130</ref>
