{{Infobox religious building | building_name = Gurdwara Sahib of San Jose | infobox_width = | image = San Jose Gurdwara Sahib (2448909577).jpg | image_size = 250px | alt = | caption = Front of Sikh Gurdwara - San Jose | map_type = | map_size = | map_caption = | location =[[San Jose, California]], [[United States|USA]] | geo = | latitude = | longitude = | religious_affiliation =[[Sikhism]] | rite = | state = | consecration_year = | heritage_designation = | website = | architecture =yes | architect = | architecture_type = | architecture_style =[[Sikh architecture]] | groundbreaking = | year_completed =1985 | construction_cost = | specifications = | capacity = | length = | width = | materials = | nrhp = | added = | refnum = | designated = }} The '''Sikh Gurdwara''' or '''Sikh Gurdwara - San Jose''' (a [[gurdwara]] is the [[Sikh]] place of worship) was founded in [[San Jose, California]], [[United States|USA]] in 1985 by leaders of the then-rapidly growing [[Santa Clara Valley]] [[Sikh]] community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sikhiwiki.org/index.php/San_Jose_Gurdwara_Sahib|title=San Jose Gurdwara Sahib - SikhiWiki, free Sikh encyclopedia.|website=www.sikhiwiki.org|language=en|accessdate=2017-08-21}}</ref> It is the largest gurdwara in [[North America]].
==History== Initially, the community met in a rented community center, but soon bought a small building in east San Jose. After buying nearby land in 1995, they decided it would be too expensive to build in the city limits, so they sold that land and bought a larger property further east. The first phase of the project of almost {{convert|20000|sqft|m2}} was completed in 2004.
The second phase was completed in April 2011,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2015/05/29/power-struggle-at-sikh-temple-in-san-jose/|title=Power struggle at Sikh temple in San Jose|last=Rodriguez|first=Joe|origyear=May 29, 2015 |date=August 12, 2016|work=The Mercury News|accessdate=|archive-url=|archivedate=|dead-url=}}</ref> making it the largest gurdwara in North America<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/20/us/20bcintel.html|title=Sikh Gurdwara Sahib Temple|last=Pellissier|first=Hank|date=2010-06-19|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2017-08-21|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> at {{convert|90000|sqft|m2}}. The chief architect and designer of the project is the late Malkiat Singh Sidhu. The largest audience at the San Jose Gurdwara was on opening day when some 20,000 people were thought to have come. [[File:Sikh Gurdwara, San Jose. Interior view.jpg|thumb|Interior view]]
