{{Italic title|reason=[[:Category:Japanese words and phrases]]}}
[[File:Gongen Zukuri.png|right|thumb|A gongen-zukuri shrine. From the top:''honden'', ''ishi-no-ma'', ''haiden''. In yellow the ridges of the roofs]]
{{nihongo|'''''Ishi-no-ma-zukuri'''''|石の間造}}, also called {{nihongo||権現造|[[gongen]]-zukuri}}, {{nihongo|''yatsumune-zukuri''|八棟造}} and {{nihongo|''miyadera-zukuri''|宮寺造}}, is a complex [[Shinto shrine]] structure in which the ''[[haiden (Shinto)|haiden]]'', or worship hall, and the [[honden]], or main sanctuary, are interconnected under the same roof in the shape of an H.<ref name="sos2">Encyclopedia of Shinto, [http://www2.kokugakuin.ac.jp/ijcc/wp/bts/bts_g.html#gongen-zukuri ''Gongen-zukuri''] accessed on December 2, 2009</ref> 

The connecting passage can be called {{nihongo|ai-no-ma|相の間|}}, {{nihongo|ishi-no-ma|石の間}}, or {{nihongo|chūden|中殿|intermediate hall}}.<ref name="Jaa"/> The floor of each of the three halls can be at a different level. If the ''ai-no-ma'' is paved with stones it is called ''ishi-no-ma'', whence the name of the style. It can, however, be paved with planks or ''[[tatami]]''. Its width is often the same as the ''honden's'', with the ''haiden'' from one to three ''[[Ken (unit)|ken]]'' wider.<ref name="Jaa"/>

This style, rather than the structure of a building, defines the relationship between member structures of a shrine. Each member then belongs to a particular architectural style. For example, the ''honden'' and ''haiden'' at {{nihongo|Ōsaki Hachiman Shrine|大崎八幡宮|Ōsaki Hachiman-gū}} are single-storied, ''irimoya-zukuri'' edifices.<ref>{{cite web
| url         = http://www.okos.co.jp/oosaki/img/english.pdf
| title       = Ōsaki Hachiman Shrine - Information in English
| publisher   = [[Ōsaki Hachiman Shrine]]
| accessdate  = 2009-11-04
}}</ref> Because they are connected by a passage called ''ishi-no-ma'' and are covered by a single roof, however, the complex is classified as belonging to the ''ishi-no-ma-zukuri'' style.

One of the oldest examples is [[Kitano Tenman-gū]] in [[Kyoto]].<ref name="sos2"/> The ''gongen-zukuri'' name comes from [[Nikkō Tōshō-gū]] in [[Nikkō]], which enshrines the Tōshō Daigongen ([[Tokugawa Ieyasu]]) and adopts this structure.<ref name="Jaa">Jaanus, [http://www.aisf.or.jp/~jaanus/deta/g/gongenzukuri.htm Gongen-zukuri], accessed on December 5, 2009</ref>

