The degree of '''[[religiosity]] in the population of the United States''' can be compared to that in other countries and compared state-by-state, based on individual self-assessment and polling data.

==Methodologies==
The [[Gallup Poll]] assesses [[religiosity]] [[Importance of religion by country|around the world]],<ref name =Theory>{{Citation |last = Truss |first = Catherine |first2 =Kerstin |last2 = Alfes
|last3 = Delbridge |first3 =Rick |last4 = Shantz |first4 =Amanda |last5 = Routledge |first5 =Emma Soane |title =Employee Engagement in Theory and Practice |publisher = Business & Economics |date=October 2013 |chapter = Employee engagement across cultures |pages = 336 }}</ref> asking "Is religion important in your daily life?" and in the United States by state, asking the degree to which respondents consider themselves to be religious. The [[Pew Research Center]] and [[Public Religion Research Institute]] have conducted studies of reported frequency of attendance to religious service.<ref name=HuffPost/> The  [[Harris Poll]] has conducted surveys of the percentage of people who believe in God.<ref name=Harris>{{cite web |last = Willett |first =Megan |title = A Fascinating New Poll Shows That Americans Are Losing Faith In God |publisher = Business Insider Inc. |date = December 17, 2013 |url = http://www.businessinsider.com/new-harris-poll-on-religion-in-america-2013-12 |accessdate = 2015-01-27 }}</ref>

==Results==
[[File:Weekly religious service attendance by US State gradient (2014).svg|thumb|350px|Church or synagogue attendance by state in 2009.]]
In a 2009 [[Gallup poll|Gallup International]] survey, 41.6% of American citizens said that they attended church or synagogue once a week or almost every week. This percentage is higher than other surveyed Western countries.<ref name=bbc20070403>{{cite news |title='One in 10' attends church weekly |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6520463.stm |publisher= BBC News |date=April 3, 2007 |accessdate= 2007-08-01 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Public Affairs |first= |authorlink= |title=NCLS releases latest estimates of church attendance |work=Media release |publisher=National Church Life Survey |date=February 28, 2004 |url=http://www.ncls.org.au/default.aspx?docid=2250&track=82083 |accessdate=2015-01-27 }}</ref> In answering, "Is religion important in your daily life," the Gallup organization reported a U.S. response of 65% reporting yes, compared to the [[United Kingdom]] with a 27% affirmative response.<ref name =Theory/> [[Church attendance]] varies considerably by state and region. The figures ranged from 63% in [[Mississippi]] to 23% in [[Vermont]]. The most religious region of the United States is [[American Samoa]] (99.3% religious).<ref name="ASamoa">[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/aq.html CIA World Factbook.] American Samoa. Retrieved 9 January 2018.</ref>
;Gallup measure of religiosity by country in 2009<ref name =Theory/>

